# Clean Code Guidelines

## NEVER
- Never use magic numbers — replace with named constants (descriptive name explaining purpose)
- Never comment what code does — make code self-documenting
- Never repeat logic — extract into reusable functions (DRY)

## ALWAYS
- Single responsibility: one function = one task, ≤20 lines, ≤4 parameters
- Meaningful names: variables/functions/classes reveal purpose, no abbreviations unless universal
- Comments explain *why*, not *what* — document APIs, complex algorithms, non-obvious side effects
- Constants at file top or dedicated constants file
- Write tests before fixing bugs; test edge cases and error conditions
- Props interface ≤7 props; split if exceeded

## PREFER
- Keep related code together in logical hierarchy
- Consistent file/folder naming conventions
- Small, focused commits with clear messages
- Meaningful branch names
- Refactor continuously; leave code cleaner than found

## AVOID
- Exposing implementation details — hide behind clear interfaces
- Nested conditionals — extract into well-named functions
- Accumulating technical debt — fix early
